@jessemyers you mean, once we have a concrete object id we can define relevant routes directly on it for things like Replace? 
That makes sense generally, however specifically for DynamoDB we ran into a situation where the DynamoDB API requires the composite key of (crawl_job_id, result_id) to access a 'result' (here crawl_job would be the subject, result would be the object of the relation). 
so the most straight-forward way of doing that seems to be to make it part of the URL scheme as in /api/crawl_job/:crawl_job_id/result/:id  - The alternative could be to require passing 'crawl_job_id' as a body field in request for /api/result/:result_id I suppose, but that seems much uglier. WDYT?

@jessemyers to be honest, it's not clear to me what we're expressing with the result of `__bool__` here.
Practically speaking, the only case where we get a `False` return value here is for `Nothing()`; and we only seem to be using `__bool__` for `EventType`'s `is_initial` property:
```
@property
def is_initial(self):
    return not bool(self.value.follows)
```
so I'm interpreting the result of `__bool__` as `is_not_initial`. In that case `AnyOf(True, False)` should indeed return `False` and not `True`; and `AnyOf(*args)` should return `False` so long as there is a `False` in there, which is why I'm using `all` here.
I don't know if this generalizes, but again I have no idea what "generalizes" means here.

The cell allows the output to be any size it wants to be.

```js
render() {
  const {data, layout} = this.props.data.toJS();
  const style = {}
  if(layout.height && !layout.autosize) {
    style.height = layout.height;
  }
  return (
    <div style={style} ref={(el) => this.el = el} /> // eslint-disable-line
  )
}
```
